Step 1: Configure SSH Access
On the Master node, generate SSH keys for secure, passwordless login:
ssh-keygen -t rsa -b 4096
Copy the public key to each slave node:
ssh-copy-id msis@172.18.181.115
ssh-copy-id msis@172.18.181.34
Verify passwordless SSH access:
ssh msis@172.18.181.115
exit
ssh msis@172.18.181.34
exit
Step 2: Install NFS Packages
On the Master node:
sudo apt update
sudo apt install nfs-kernel-server -y
 On the Slave nodes:
sudo apt update
sudo apt install nfs-common -y
Step 3: Configure NFS Shared Directory on Master
Create a shared directory and set permissions:
sudo mkdir -p /nfs/shared
sudo chmod 777 /nfs/shared
Edit the NFS export configuration:
sudo nano /etc/exports
Add the following entries, allowing the slave nodes to access the shared directory:
/nfs/shared 172.18.181.115(rw,sync,no_subtree_check)
/nfs/shared 172.18.181.34(rw,sync,no_subtree_check)
Apply the configuration and restart the NFS service:
sudo exportfs -a
sudo systemctl restart nfs-kernel-server
sudo exportfs -v  # verify exports

Step 4: Mount the Shared Directory on Slaves
On each slave node, create the mount point and mount the shared directory:
sudo mkdir -p /nfs/shared
sudo mount 172.18.181.111:/nfs/shared /nfs/shared/
cd /nfs/shared/
touch testfile
ls
Replace 172.18.181.111 with the Master node's IP address.
Step 5: Verify NFS Functionality
    1. On the Master node, create a test file:
cd /nfs/shared/
touch masterfile

    2. On the Slave node, check if the file is accessible:
cd /nfs/shared/
ls
